HR SUPPORTPIC: Fleet Personnel ManagerAlternate: Senior HR Executive1) Provide updated crew list, including list of supernumeraries on board.2) Provide details of Nationalities on board.3) Provide brief bio-data and experience details of the four senior officers on board.4) Prepare list of next to kin and their contact details.5) Notify crewing offices and crew families as required and keep them informed of all the developments at frequent intervals,especially if any injuries or casualties have occurred amongst the crew.6) Notify the Crew national authority as required by the local employment regulations.7) Provide photos of all personnel on board.8) Co-ordinate travel arrangements, as required for the designated Field team.9) ERT members must always have proper documents visas, credit cards, etc. readily available at short notice.10) Check if any of the officers who have recently worked on their ship are on leave and establish contact with them if their assistancemay be required to collect information on the ship.11) Appoint Agents, as required.12) Close Liaison on the above issues with ‘Incident Commander’ and ‘Emergency Response Adviser’.11. IT DEPARTMENTPIC: Systems AdministratorAlternate: Assistant Systems AdministratorEnsure following equipment working in ERT room:1) Email, Telephones, fax and scanner.2) Primary and alternate (Internet data card) internet facility to be provided.3) Projection system4) Actuate Blind Site on Company Web.12. INCIDENT AWAY TEAMPIC: Technical SuperintendentAlternate: Back up Technical Superintendent 1) To travel to the site and set up a field command post if so required.2) Assists Master in dealing with casualty and to keep Planning Chief posted.3) Liaises with external parties available at scene to utilize all available resources to deal effectively with contingency.4) Coordinate clean up jobs with third party contractors.5) To provide post casualty assistance to company asset.6) To participate in the post incident analysis.7) The field team shall liaise and consult with the Owners’ representative on site.8) All major actions taken shall be in consultation with the Owners’ representative on site and the head office. 9) The field team will keep the head office updated at least once a day with full report on the day’s events.7.4RECORD KEEPING1. Events Log: A clear and concise ‘Events Log’ is essential to guide the incident management decision process and the continuingcollective activities of the company’s response team. The “Casualty ERT Record – OQ 10” is to be maintained by the ERT.2. Emergency Checklist for Office: The “Emergency Checklist for Office – OQ 11” is to be filled up to ensure that all necessaryaspects are being adequately dealt with.3. Situation Report: Incident Commander must publish ‘Situation Report (SitRep) on a regular basis using the form “SituationReport - OQ 12”. Refer to Section 7.7 for details on preparing the SitRep.7.5PROCEDURES FOR DEALING WITH EMERGENCIES
